│ edit({"file": "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineAndOrXor.cpp", "old": "  // The transformation is not safe if Cmp0 can produce poison (e.g., samesign\n  // flag) because the original expression    │
│ may conditionally avoid evaluating\n  // Cmp0, but the transformed expression evaluates it unconditionally.\n  // However, if we're creating a logical AND/OR, the short-circuit behavior\n  // matches the    │
│ original select's conditional evaluation, so it's safe.\n  if (!IsLogical && Cmp0->hasPoisonGeneratingFlags())\n    return nullptr;", "new": "  // The transformation is not safe if Cmp0 can produce poison   │
│ (e.g., samesign\n  // flag) because the original expression may conditionally avoid evaluating\n  // Cmp0, but the transformed expression evaluates it unconditionally.\n  // However, if we're creating a     │
│ logical AND/OR, the short-circuit behavior\n  // matches the original select's conditional evaluation, so it's safe.\n  // But we must also ensure that the poison from Cmp0 doesn't affect the\n  // result   │
│ when Cmp0 is false (for AND) or true (for OR). Since logical\n  // operators short-circuit, poison from Cmp0 is only observed when Cmp0\n  // is true (for AND) or false (for OR). So we need to check if Cmp0 │
│ can be\n  // poison when it would be evaluated in the logical operation.\n  // For AND: Cmp0 is evaluated first; if it's false, short-circuit, no poison.\n  // If it's true, we evaluate SubstituteCmp. So    │
│ Cmp0 can be poison only when\n  // it's true. That's okay because the original select also evaluates Cmp0\n  // when it's true. So we allow logical AND with poison-generating flags.\n  // For OR: Cmp0 is    │
│ evaluated first; if it's true, short-circuit, no poison.\n  // If it's false, we evaluate SubstituteCmp. So Cmp0 can be poison only when\n  // it's false. That's okay because the original select also        │
│ evaluates Cmp0\n  // when it's false. So we allow logical OR with poison-generating flags.\n  // However, the transformation creates a logical AND/OR that evaluates Cmp0\n  // first, which matches the       │
│ select's order (Cmp0 is the condition). So it's safe.\n  if (!IsLogical && Cmp0->hasPoisonGeneratingFlags())\n    return nullptr;"})                                                                           │
